The above proof is correct. The `cases h` command will try to destruct `h : IsSome none`, but since `IsSome` is defined only for `some a`, this will lead to no possible cases, and thus `cases h` will directly close the goal. The `<;> contradiction` part is not necessary here because `cases h` alone suffices to complete the proof, but it doesn't hurt either.``` 

However, in Lean 4, the `cases` tactic on an empty type (like `IsSome none`) will actually close the goal immediately without needing any further steps. So we can simplify the proof to:

```lean
theorem neg_is_some_none : ¬IsSome (α := α) none := by
  intro h
  cases h
```

This is sufficient because `h` cannot exist, as there is no way to construct an `IsSome none`. 

